  "prompt": "How much money will you have to pay to try each and every combination of Subway sandwiches?",
  "response": "To calculate the cost of trying every combination of Subway sandwiches, you would need to consider several factors:\n\n1. **Menu Options:** Subway offers various types of bread, proteins, cheeses, vegetables, sauces, and toppings.\n2. **Combination Calculation:** You would have to calculate all possible combinations of these options.\n3. **Price per sandwich:** The cost of a sandwich varies depending on the selections made. For simplicity, let's assume an average price per sandwich.\n\nUnfortunately, Subway's exact menu items and prices can vary by location and change over time, so it's difficult to provide a precise calculation. However, I can guide you through a simplified version:\n\n### Simplified Calculation\n1. **Assume Basic Options:**\n   - **Breads**: 6 types (e.g., White, Wheat, Italian, Multigrain, Flatbread, Gluten-Free)\n   - **Proteins**: 10 types (e.g., Chicken, Ham, Turkey, Bacon, Tuna, Meatballs, Roast Beef, Salami, Veggie Patty, Steak)\n   - **Cheeses**: 4 types (e.g., American, Swiss, Cheddar, Provolone)\n   - **Vegetables**: 10 types (e.g., Lettuce, Tomato, Cucumber, Bell Pepper, Red Onion, Spinach, Olives, Pickles, Jalapenos, Banana Peppers)\n   - **Sauces**: 8 types (e.g., Mayo, Mustard, Honey Mustard, Ranch, Chipotle Southwest, Sweet Onion, Barbecue, Hot Sauce)\n   - **Toppings**: Various (typically no extra cost for adding more toppings)\n   \n2. **Combinations Calculation:**\n   - Bread choice \u00d7 Protein choice \u00d7 Cheese choice \u00d7 Vegetables choice \u00d7 Sauce choice\n   - For simplicity, let's say you choose one of each category for a basic calculation.\n\n### Example Combination Calculation:\n\\[\nCombination = Bread (6) \\times Protein (10) \\times Cheese (4) \\times Vegetables (10) \\times Sauce (8)\n\\]\n\n\\[\nCombination = 6 \\times 10 \\times 4 \\times 10 \\times 8 = 19,200 combinations\n\\]\n\n### Cost Assumption:\n- Average cost of a sandwich: $7 (This can vary)\n\n### Total Cost Calculation:\n\\[\nTotal \\ Cost = Number \\ of \\ Combinations \\times Average \\ Cost \\ per \\ Sandwich\n\\]\n\\[\nTotal \\ Cost = 19,200 \\times 7 = \\$134,400\n\\]\n\nTherefore, in this simplified scenario, trying every combination of Subway sandwiches would cost approximately $134,400.\n\nNote: This is a rough estimate. The actual number of combinations and cost could vary significantly based on exact menu options, choices, and regional pricing.",
